column2: Bertrand le Grande (Knights of the Realm)
They have much experience charging from the beachhead and flanking enemy positions on the shoreline.
Marines of a thousand voyages, they have learnt much from the sea including its mortal poisons.
These Marines have found fire, works just as well against warriors as it does against enemy ships.
Only Shadow Warriors and the Sisters of Averlorn are considered their betters, though this is not always been proven to be true.
Only the greatest of Asuryan spearmen may join the company of the Bright Falcon.
Former Lothern Sea Guards, their skill was unsurpassed with a spear and handpicked to join this illustrious company.
Boglars made a pact with the cyclopean creatures and now they fight side by side, why the Fimir would make deals with such puny creatures is a mystery.
Dragon Ogres are incredibly ancient and very powerful creatures, some chose to reside in the frostbitten glaciers of Norsca until their Dark master beckon them forth.
The Finmor usually command small bands of Shearls or just use them as slaves in their communities.
Devoted to the Dark Master Be'Lakor, these fanatics worship their god blindly.
Balefiends revel in the instability they create between worlds, urging the Dark Gods to favour the Fimir once again.
Balefiends revel in the instability they create between worlds, urging the Dark Gods to favour the Fimir once again.
The slave caste of the Fimir. While lower in ranks, Shearls are still a fearsome foe.
Tall as a troll and easily as strong, Mistmor are prized as defenders of Fimir settlements.
Fanatic worshippers of daemonic powers. Their clans destroyed, they raid and pillage with the sole purpose of killing and reproducing in cruel ways.
Rumors tell of creatures living near a haunted, icy lake in the northern part of Albion. The native folks call them Gharnu's Demon-Friends.
When Killing Eye clan was left without a leader, the retinues of Fimm warriors set out to seek a new Meargh or their ultimate annihilation.
Of the Fimm warrior caste only proven veterans may be elevated to guarding the upper echelons of society.
The Guards are sometimes found leading bands of Orcs and Goblins, but are dangerous enough even when encountered singly.
The Fianna are the elite of the Fimm Warriors, hand-picked, sometimes at birth, sometimes as a result of some great deed.
They terrorize the swamps, stalking livestock and lonely travelers until the daemonic hounds are summoned by the Fimir, where they know they will dine well on battlefield carcasses.

These entities watch with envious eyes towards the mortal kingdoms, waiting with unblinking patience for their chance to wreak destruction and dismay upon the world and to feed upon the misery that they have wrought.
Their blood thickens as your warriors fill with the Rage of Khorne!
The fires of Chaos swell deep within its most powerful of beings.

Those few who have confronted a Bloodthirster and survived commonly recall an overwhelming impression of vast size and unchecked barbarity, of roaring and snarling death riding upon stygian wings that eclipse the sun. A Bloodthirster’s ruddy skin is covered with coarse fur and brass armour, slick and gleaming with the blood of innumerable victims. This armour is forged upon the Daemon’s flesh by Khorne himself and thereafter becomes a living part of the Daemon, even whilst maintaining a brutal intelligence of its own. As such, even the Bloodthirster’s armour is wrathful and longs for slaughter.
